questionTemplates.text:
F: Why do you say your dog is like a cat.
M: Because it plays with cats and it is afraid of dogs.
{a}

M: OK, so I think that's everything: three oranges, four apples, one pineapple, and a watermelon.
W: Yes, that should do it. This is going to be the best fruit salad ever!
{a}

F: Are you a party member?
M: I joined it two years ago.
{a}

M: Your yard is always so beautiful, Cathy. You must have a gardener.
W: Oh, no. It would cost at least $50 a month to hire someone to do the work, so I do most of it myself. I enjoy taking care of the flowers, but I have to force myself to do the weeding and cut the grass.
{a}

W: It's a wonderful trip.
M: I think so.
{a}

W: Why don't you go to work?
M: I have to find one first.
{a}

M: Those oranges look nice. How much are they?
W: They're sixty cents a pound.
{a}

M: I just received an Email from one of my former classmates. I was surprised. I hadn't heard from him for ages.
W: Well, I've been out of touch with most of my old friends. Only one or two still drop me a line occasionally.
{a}

W: The space shuttle is taking off tomorrow.
M: I know, this is another routine mission. It is first flight with four years ago.
{a}

M: How much money will I have to spend to rent an apartment in America? I'll only have $500 a month.
W: Your rent should be about a quarter of that.
{a}

M: I'm going to the school and I'll pass the supermarket on my way back. Do you need to buy anything,mum? I heard you said there's no coffee at home.
W: You father bought it. Please buy a kilo of sugar, two kilos of rice and a pack of tea, Matthew.
{a}

W: How do you like the car I just bought?
M: Well, it seems to run well, but I think it needs a new paint job.
{a}

W: You look like you are freezing to death. Why don't you put this on?
M: Thank you, it was so warm at noon, I didn't expect the weather to change so quickly.
{a}

M: I have to go to Prof. Hudson's office to discuss my thesis. If time allows, I'd like to go to the movies with you when I come back.
W: I don't think I can make it. I'm going shopping with Jane right now.
{a}

W: Bob, the flowers you keep look much better than those I keep.
M: I take good care of them and my wife also waters them frequently.
{a}

M: Well, the holiday is well soon be here.
W: Yes, isn't it exciting by this time next week, we'll be on the plane?
{a}

M: When is the movie supposed to start?
W: Take it easy. It won't start until 10: 30. We've still got 20 minutes.
{a}

M: Where's Joan? She said she would be here at 3, but now it's 3:30. She must have missed the train.
W: I think so. I hope she doesn't miss the next one, otherwise she'll be late for the opening address at the conference.
{a}

M: Paul's been taking 5 courses, but he's decided to drop one of them at the end of this semester.
F: That may be for the best.
{a}

W: Hi, Harry. You're taking a camera for tomorrow's trip, aren't you?
M: Yes. And I have asked Max to bring pens and paper. You know our teacher wants us to take notes.
{a}

W: How long will you take to finish your homework?
M: If it takes Alice an hour to do the homework, it will surely take the rest of us two hours.
{a}

W: Three letters of recommendation are required to apply to graduate schools. I was wondering if the one professor Smith wrote for me last year could still be used.
M: It's a bit dated. You'd better submit a recent one.
{a}

M: You really seem to enjoy your literature class.
W: You're right. It has opened a new world for me. I'm exposed to the thoughts of some of the world's best writers. I've never read so much in my life.
{a}

W: Excuse me, I'm trying to get to the courthouse and I think I'm going the wrong way. Should I have turned left on Monroe Street?
M: No, no. You're all right. Just keep going straight on Fourth Avenue until you get to the Post Office, and turn left there.
{a}

M: The new baby must be keeping you up at all hours of the night.
W: She's been pretty good since my mother moved in, and she's sleeping for a longer time at night. It's my thoughts as a mother that keep me awake at night.
{a}

M: I hear John left his cat in your care while he's on vacation abroad. How are you getting along with it?
W: Well, it never comes when I call it. It spills its food and sheds all over the place. I can't wait till John gets back.
{a}

M: Bill was a great guy. He was drowned while rescuing a child from the icy water of the river yesterday.
W: Well, as far as I know, that was not the first dangerous situation he was in.
{a}
